Description:
Changes in the kind of use, or the intensity of use of terrestrial, limnic and marine ecosystems (e.g. intensification or extensification of agriculture, fishing vs. overfishing) affecting global nature, nature’s contributions to people and a good quality of life in a positive or negative direction. This includes 
* landscape/seascape transformations (transformations into a different kind of ecosystem, causing irreversible or at least significant and long lasting changes to nature, nature’s contributions to people (changes of contributions and of beneficiaries) and a the quality of life); 
* cultivation intensity changes (the kind of use remains basically the same (agriculture, forestry, leisure, etc.), but the use intensity increases or decreases as a direct result of human management decisions); 
* direct exploitation and extraction (as in ecosystem products, surface and ground water resources, etc).
